    title: "Nephrolithiasis Prevention: 24-Hour Urine & Dietary Strategies",
    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Nephrolithiasis Prevention: 24-Hour Urine & Dietary Strategies", content: "Kidney stone recurrence prevention is grounded in modifying the urinary chemical environment to reduce supersaturation of lithogenic solutes and enhance protective inhibitors. The 24-hour urine metabolic evaluation is the cornerstone of personalized prevention, quantifying the key stone-promoting factors (calcium, oxalate, uric acid, sodium, volume, pH) and protective factors (citrate, magnesium) that determine crystallization risk. Supersaturation — the ratio of dissolved solute concentration to the thermodynamic solubility product — is the fundamental physical-chemical driver: when supersaturation exceeds the formation product (upper limit of metastability), spontaneous crystallization occurs. Each dietary and pharmacological intervention targets specific components of this equation. Increased fluid intake (targeting urine output greater than 2.5 L/day) is the single most effective intervention, diluting all solute concentrations and reducing supersaturation across all stone types. Dietary sodium restriction (less than 2300 mg/day) reduces urinary calcium excretion because sodium and calcium share reabsorption pathways in the proximal tubule — every 100 mEq of sodium excreted obligates approximately 25 mg of additional calcium loss. Dietary calcium should be maintained at 1000-1200 mg/day from food sources, consumed with meals: intestinal calcium binds dietary oxalate, forming insoluble calcium oxalate in the gut lumen, preventing oxalate absorption and reducing urinary oxalate (paradoxically, calcium restriction increases stone risk by raising urinary oxalate). Citrate is the primary endogenous crystallization inhibitor: it chelates urinary calcium (reducing available calcium for crystal formation) and directly inhibits calcium oxalate and calcium phosphate crystal growth and aggregation. Potassium citrate supplementation (typically 30-60 mEq/day) corrects hypocitraturia and alkalinizes urine. Thiazide diuretics (hydrochlorothiazide, chlorthalidone) reduce urinary calcium excretion by 50% through enhanced proximal tubular calcium reabsorption secondary to volume contraction. Allopurinol reduces urinary uric acid excretion by inhibiting xanthine oxidase, preventing both uric acid stone formation and the heterogeneous nucleation of calcium oxalate stones on uric acid crystal nidi. Urine alkalinization to pH 6.5-7.0 with potassium citrate can dissolve existing uric acid stones (uric acid pKa is 5.35 — at pH 6.5, nearly all uric acid is in the soluble ionized form)." },
